{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568863"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:23:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:23:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21479"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21479"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.67,0.23,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14348"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102474"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14348"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21479"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84948"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"212"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12097"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"35834"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43750"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102474"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-day history of a severe, throbbing headache localised to the right side of her head. She reports associated nausea, vomiting, and photophobia. She has a history of migraine with aura since adolescence, typically experiencing one attack every two months. She is currently 14 weeks pregnant with her first child. Prior to pregnancy, she successfully managed her migraines with sumatriptan, which provided complete relief within two hours. She has not tried any medication for this attack as she was concerned about taking medications in pregnancy. She has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears uncomfortable with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for her acute migraine attack?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Codeine phosphate","Paracetamol with metoclopramide","Sumatriptan","Ergotamine","Ibuprofen"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a typical migraine attack during the second trimester of pregnancy. Management of migraines in pregnancy requires careful consideration of medication safety for both mother and fetus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol with metoclopramide\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line treatment for acute migraine attacks in pregnancy. Paracetamol is considered safe throughout pregnancy, and metoclopramide helps with both the nausea associated with migraine and may enhance the absorption of paracetamol. This combination is recommended as the initial approach before considering other medications with less established safety profiles in pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESumatriptan\u003C/strong\u003E (and other triptans) have limited data regarding safety in pregnancy, though the available evidence is relatively reassuring with no documented increase in congenital malformations. However, they should only be used sporadically in pregnancy when other safer options have failed and when they are the only agents that successfully treat an acute attack. In this case, the patient has not tried any medication therefore would be advisable to try simple analgesia first. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIbuprofen\u003C/strong\u003E and other non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs can be used in short courses for acute attacks in the first and second trimesters. However, they are not first-line and should be avoided in the third trimester due to risks of premature closure of the ductus arteriosus and other fetal complications. Given that safer alternatives exist, ibuprofen would not be the most appropriate first choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErgotamine\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in pregnancy due to its vasoconstrictive properties and potential to cause uterine contractions, which may lead to fetal harm or pregnancy complications. It should never be used during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECodeine phosphate\u003C/strong\u003E is generally considered safe for short-term use in pregnancy, but it carries risks of maternal constipation and potential for dependence with prolonged use. Additionally, it may not be as effective for migraine as the first-line options. It would be a reasonable alternative if the patient cannot tolerate or has contraindications to the first-line therapy, but it is not the most appropriate initial choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor patients with frequent migraine attacks during pregnancy, prophylaxis should be considered. Low-dose aspirin (75 -100mg daily) is safe and effective for migraine prophylaxis in pregnancy and can be considered as a first-line prophylactic agent. Aspirin also has the benefit of reducing the risk of pre-eclampsia, risk for pre-eclampsia is increased with history of migraine. Beta-blockers such as propranolol may also be used in resistant cases without contraindications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Paracetamol with metoclopramide is first-line treatment for acute migraine attacks in pregnancy.","Sumatriptan can be used sporadically in pregnancy if it is the only effective agent for a patient\u0027s migraines.","Low-dose aspirin (75-100 mg daily) is safe and effective for migraine prophylaxis in pregnancy and also reduces the risk of pre-eclampsia"],"references":["Nelson-Piercy C. Handbook of obstetric medicine. 6th ed. Boca Raton: CRC Press; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84948"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21479"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84948"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-12T22:02:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T22:02:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14348"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102474"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management